Your question is pretty broad, but in general you don&#39;t need to have your entire application be Vue to create a widget in Vue. If you need to configure your widget, consider creating a global object for it. Now you can read `window.Widget` in your application and use whatever is in there.

    &lt;script&gt;
    window.Widget = {
      backgroundColor: &#39;#fcba03&#39;,
      nrOfPolarBears: 3,
    }
    &lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;script src=&quot;link/to/your/app.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

Alternatively, if you have to load your widget in an iframe, you have limited configurability via the query string of the url you retrieve:

    &lt;iframe src=&quot;link/to/index.html?backgroundcolor=%23fcba03&amp;nrofpolarbears=3&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    // App.vue
    const queryParams = window.location.search.substr(1).split(&#39;&amp;&#39;).reduce(
      (acc, part) =&gt; {
        const [key, val] = part.split(&#39;=&#39;, 2)
        acc[decodeURIComponent(key)] = decodeURIComponent(val);
    
        return acc;
      },
      {}
    )
    console.log(queryParams.backgroundcolor);

